english:
  title: A Discourse on the Sword
  author: Seok Sik-yeong-am
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A master named Jungu once gave a wanderer a sword. The wanderer treasured it greatly, clutching it in his hands throughout the day, never setting it down, and placing it beside his bed at night.

    One dawn, a figure entered through the gate—a scholar's face beneath a warrior's garb. He neither hurried nor bowed at the sight of the wanderer.

    "A scholar comes," said the wanderer. "What teaching brings you here?"

    "My name is Zhuangzi," replied the visitor. "I have some skill with the sword. Yesterday I demonstrated before King Zhao, and he declared my swordsmanship unrivaled under heaven. He elevated me to his hall and granted me food and drink. Now hearing that you love the sword, I have come to show you mine."

    "What sword do you possess?" asked the wanderer.

    "I have three swords," answered Zhuangzi. "The sword of the Son of Heaven, the sword of the princes, and the sword of the common people." He elaborated on each.

    The wanderer raised his hand. "Enough. Your swords are merely the periphery of swordsmanship. Yet there are others beyond these three?"

    Thrice Zhuangzi attempted to answer, but could not. His countenance grew sorrowful. At last he spoke: "Forgive me, but what sword do you possess?"

    "The wanderer's sword," came the reply, "is these three and yet one more—making four. All four are the root, not the branches. How can one speak of mastery by grasping only the periphery while missing the source?"

    Zhuangzi prostrated three times, rose, and bowed deeply again. "I am your student," he said respectfully. "What are the names of these four swords?"

    "They are," said the wanderer, "the Sword of the Tathagata, the Sword of the Bodhisattva, the Sword of the Patriarch, and the Sword of the Wanderer."

    "What is the Sword of the Tathagata?" asked Zhuangzi.

    The wanderer began: "The Sword of the Tathagata has for its point billions upon billions of worlds. For its blade, the continents of sentient life. For its spine, countless paradises. For its cross-guard, the four directions. For its pommel, the mountain Sumeru itself. No span of time can measure it, no expanse of space can contain it. The ocean cannot encircle it, nor iron mountains bind it. It is forged in the immutable law-body, inscribed with boundless wisdom-form, and wielded through enlightened activity. When thrust, nothing stands before it. When raised, nothing rises above it. When pressed down, nothing descends beneath it. When swung, nothing moves beside it. With a single use of this sword, all reaches the ultimate reality above, and sustains the illusory world below, keeping the dharma-realm perfectly still. This is the Sword of the Tathagata."

    "What of the Sword of the Bodhisattva?" asked Zhuangzi.

    "The Sword of the Bodhisattva," replied the wanderer, "has courageous spirit for its point, keen discernment for its blade, uprightness for its spine, patience for its cross-guard, and steadfast resolve for its pommel. It is wrapped in three incalculable ages, adorned with fifty-five stages, encircled by the ocean of meditation, and bound by mountains of virtue. It is tempered through four forms of wisdom, engraved with four eloquences, opened through six paramitas, and wielded through great vows and greater deeds. When thrust, nothing stands before it. When raised, nothing rises above it. When pressed down, nothing descends beneath it. When swung, nothing moves beside it. With a single use of this sword, the fruit of enlightenment ripens above, delusion is severed below, and the distance to Buddhahood grows short. This is the Sword of the Bodhisattva."

    "And the Sword of the Patriarch?" pressed Zhuangzi.

    "The Sword of the Patriarch," said the wanderer, "has no point, yet it pierces. It has no blade, yet it cuts. It has no spine, yet it supports. It has no cross-guard, yet it holds firm. It has no pommel, yet it stands. Nothing wraps it, adorns it, encircles it, or binds it. One cannot forge it, cannot wield it, cannot speak of it, cannot unfold it, cannot move it. One wishes to thrust, but cannot thrust. One wishes to press down, but cannot press down. One wishes to raise, but cannot raise. One wishes to swing, but cannot swing. With a single use of this sword, the Tathagata turns a blind eye and the Bodhisattva erases all traces. It stands alone in the world with nothing to match it. This is the Sword of the Patriarch."

    "And the Sword of the Wanderer?" asked Zhuangzi eagerly.

    "The Sword of the Wanderer," began the wanderer, "is called the Grasped Sword—and this is it." He drew forth a blade: iron edge with silver fittings, cast and inscribed by the three sacred craftsmen, adorned with celestial bodies upon its guard, twin dragons decorating its mouth. Its grip was of red wood bound with green silk, its length less than a foot, its width less than an inch.

    Before the wanderer could finish speaking, Zhuangzi sprang up. "How does it differ from my sword of the common people?"

    The wanderer smiled. "You are indeed a simple man. Know you not? The sword of the common people is the periphery of the periphery, while the Sword of the Wanderer is the root of roots. The difference transcends heaven and earth. Listen further: this sword is sometimes great, sometimes small, sometimes soft, sometimes hard. When the Tathagata uses it, it becomes the Sword of the Tathagata. When the Bodhisattva uses it, it becomes the Sword of the Bodhisattva. When the Patriarch uses it, it becomes the Sword of the Patriarch. When the Son of Heaven, princes, and common folk use it, it becomes theirs. Yet it never leaves the Way. In one stroke, whether all the people of the world fall or all the people of the world rise—both are yours to choose. Do you believe me?"

    The wanderer made one fluid stroke with his sword. Zhuangzi's spirit scattered like startled birds. He fled. When pursued, he had become a butterfly, fluttering softly through the air.
